uhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the United States and other developed nations spending as much as 14 percent of their GDP on medical care, economists and policy analysts are asking what these countries are getting in return. Yet it remains frustrating and difficult to measure the productivity of the medical care service industries. This volume takes aim at that problem, while taking stock of where we are in our attempts to solve it. Much of this analysis focuses on the capacity to measure the value of technological change and other health care innovations. A key finding suggests that growth in health care spending has coincided with an increase in products and services that together reduce mortality rates and promote additional health gains. Concerns over the apparent increase in unit prices of medical care may thus understate positive impacts on consumer welfare. When appropriately adjusted for such quality improvements, health care prices may actually have fallen. Provocative and compelling, this volume not only clarifies one of the more nebulous issues in health care analysis, but in so doing addresses an area of pressing public policy concern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness. 0aHealth. 0aMedical care, Cost of. 0aMedical care. 0aSocial sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAnis, Aslam H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndt, Ernst R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndt, Ernst R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBusch, Susan H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCockburn, Iain M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, David M., econtributor.4ctb